    "summary": "The Neo-Assyrian Empire (911–609 BC) was the first empire to dominate the entire ancient Near East — Mesopotamia, the Levant, Egypt, and Anatolia — and the most powerful military state of the first millennium BC, renowned for the ferocity of its armies, the sophistication of its administration, and the systematic terror it deployed against resisters. Beginning with Adad-nirari II and accelerating under [[event:1899|Tiglath-Pileser III]] and his successors, Assyria developed the ancient world's first professional standing army with siege engineers, cavalry, iron weapons, and coordinated combined-arms tactics.\n\nAssyrian imperial ideology was built on display of overwhelming force: reliefs in royal palaces depicted battles, sieges, and the torture of prisoners in graphic detail. Mass deportations of conquered populations (hundreds of thousands were moved to Assyria) undermined regional resistance while providing labor for building projects. Yet Assyria was also a center of literacy and learning: [[event:1902|Ashurbanipal's Library]] at Nineveh was the ancient world's first systematic library, collecting thousands of clay tablets with literary, scientific, and omen texts. At its height under [[event:1901|Sennacherib and Nineveh]], the empire stretched from Egypt to the Persian Gulf. The rapid [[event:3064|Fall of Assyria]] in 612–609 BC to a coalition of Babylonians and Medes was so complete that within decades the great Assyrian cities lay in ruins, their populations dispersed — a collapse that astonished ancient observers and has fascinated historians ever since.",
